Nope not quiet it doesn't set

last_stride_y = stride_y;
last_stride_x = stride_x;
last_padding_y = padding_y;
last_padding_x = padding_x;

 that's the only "setup" the CPU implementation seems to do.

You could call this one in the other one to make it nicer and reduce code duplication yes. 
I thought about that but left it out for now.

The reason why is there is a much larger difference in the CUDA version but I have to keep the same signatures as interface between the two have to stay the same.

It's can return `str`:

```python
if int(quantity) == 1:
        return self.random.choice(hashtags)
```

I think this would be better structured if we dropped the `mode` concept and instead used subclasses of base class to implement each benchmark.

```
class BaseERC20Benchmark(BaseBenchmark):
    def execute(self):
        ... # setup code here
        self._do_benchmark(...)

class ERC20TransferBenchmark(BaseERC20Benchmark):
    name = 'ERC20 Transfer Benchmark'

    def _do_benchmark(self):
        ... # logic for the `tranfer` test
```

We may just have a "new" to contain both "added" and "changed". Say
ChangelogEntry {
  new = OperatorBinding {
    op_type = "Slice",
    op_def = "_NewSlice",
  }
}

In the "new", the key is always over-written, if the key exists, then it's removing the old one and change to new one, if the key does not exist, it's purely adding a new one, and "removed" contains keys totally removed.
